# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloudflare-durable-objects
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded in 2009 by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company went public on the New York Stock Exchange in 2019 under the ticker symbol NET.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has since expanded its offerings to include edge computing through its Workers platform, a public DNS resolver (1.1.1.1), and a VPN-like service known as WARP.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In recent years, the company has integrated artificial intelligence into its infrastructure, acquiring companies such as Replicate and launching tools to manage AI bots and scrapers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] According to W3Techs, Cloudflare is used by approximately 21.3% of all websites on the Internet as of January 2026.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company has been the subject of controversy regarding its policy of content neutrality.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has also faced criticism and litigation regarding copyright infringement by websites using its services, notably losing a lawsuit against Japanese publishers in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company experienced significant global outages in late 2025 which disrupted services for major platforms internationally.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare was founded on July 26, 2009, by Matthew Prince, Lee Holloway, and Michelle Zatlyn.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Prince and Holloway had previously collaborated on Project Honey Pot, a product of Unspam Technologies that partly inspired the basis of Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2009, the company was venture-capital funded.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On August 15, 2019, Cloudflare submitted its S-1 filing for an initial public offering on the New York Stock Exchange under the stock ticker NET.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] It opened for public trading on September 13, 2019, at $15 per share.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare co-founder and COO Michelle Zatlyn was named president.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has acquired web-services and security companies, including StopTheHacker (February 2014), CryptoSeal (June 2014), Eager Platform Co.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Replicate (November 2025), and Human Native (January 2026).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Since at least 2017, Cloudflare has used a wall of lava lamps at its San Francisco headquarters as a source of randomness for encryption keys, alongside double pendulums at its London offices and a Geiger counter at its Singapore offices.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The lava lamp installation implements the Lavarand method, where a camera transforms the unpredictable shapes of the "lava" blobs into a digital image.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In Q4 2022, Cloudflare provided paid services to 162,086 customers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In October 2024, Cloudflare won a lawsuit against patent troll Sable Networks.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Sable paid Cloudflare $225,000, granted it a royalty-free license to its patent portfolio, and dedicated its patents to the public by abandoning its patent rights.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In November 2025, it was announced Cloudflare had agreed to acquire Replicate, a San Francisco–based platform that enables software developers to run, fine-tune, and deploy open-source machine-learning models via an API without managing infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare released an analysis regarding BGP routing leaks observed from the Venezuelan state-owned ISP CANTV (AS8048), which occurred on January 2 coincides with the arrest of Nicolás Maduro.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] While some security researchers had speculated that the outages were linked to U.S. cyber operations, Cloudflare's data indicated that the anomalies were consistent with a pattern of "insufficient routing export and import policies" by the ISP rather than malicious external interference.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In January 2026, Cloudflare acquired Human Native, an AI data marketplace that brokers transactions between developers and content creators, for an undisclosed amount.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On January 16, 2026, Cloudflare acquired The Astro Technology Company, the developers behind the open-source web framework Astro.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In May 2026, Cloudflare announced the elimination of approximately 1,100 positions, around 20 percent of its workforce, in a restructuring the company attributed to the rapid adoption of artificial intelligence tools.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The announcement coincided with the company's first-quarter 2026 earnings, which reported a record $639.8 million in quarterly revenue, a 34 percent year-over-year increase.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] CEO Matthew Prince stated the cuts were not driven by performance concerns but reflected roles made obsolete by AI, and that Cloudflare expected to employ more people by the end of 2027 than at any point during 2026.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides network and security products for consumers and businesses, utilizing edge computing, reverse proxies for web traffic, data center interconnects, and a content distribution network to serve content across its network of servers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] It supports transport layer protocols TCP, UDP, QUIC, and many application layer protocols such as DNS over HTTPS, SMTP, and HTTP/2 with support for HTTP/2 Server Push.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] As of 2023, Cloudflare handles an average of 45 million HTTP requests per second.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] As of 2024, Cloudflare servers are powered by AMD EPYC 9684X processors.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare also provides analysis and reports on large-scale outages, including Verizon's October 2024 outage.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released an open-source CMS called EmDash, intended to align with serverless and edge-based architecture.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2023, Cloudflare launched "Workers AI", a framework allowing for use of Nvidia GPU's within Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare launched a tool that prevents bots from scraping websites.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] To build automatic bot detector models, the company analyzed "AI" bots and crawler traffic.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company also launched an "AI" assistant to generate charts based on queries by leveraging "Workers AI".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced plans in September 2024 to launch a marketplace where website owners can sell "AI" model providers access to scrape their site's content.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In March 2025, Cloudflare announced a new feature called "AI Labyrinth", which combats unauthorized "AI" data scraping by serving fake "AI"-generated content to LLM bots.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In July, the company rolled out a permission-based setting to allow websites to automatically block online bots from scraping data and content.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare released AutoRAG into beta in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] AutoRAG (retrieval augmented generation) creates a vector database of a website's unstructured content to identify relationships between concepts.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] It is part of an initiative with Microsoft, alongside their NLWeb standard, to make websites easier for people and automated systems to query.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare and GoDaddy partnered in April 2026 to enable AI Crawl Control features on GoDaddy hosted websites.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] This would allow site owners to decide how AI bot crawlers interact with their content.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare provides free and paid DDoS mitigation services that protect customers from distributed denial of service (DDoS) attacks.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare received media attention in June 2011 for providing DDoS mitigation for the website of LulzSec, a black hat hacking group.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In March 2013, The Spamhaus Project was targeted by a DDoS attack that Cloudflare reported exceeded 300 gigabits per second (Gbit/s).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Patrick Gilmore, of Akamai, stated that at the time it was "the largest publicly announced DDoS attack in the history of the Internet".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] While trying to defend Spamhaus against the DDoS attacks, Cloudflare ended up being attacked as well; Google and other companies eventually came to Spamhaus' defense and helped it to absorb the unprecedented amount of attack traffic.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2014, Cloudflare began providing free DDoS mitigation for artists, activists, journalists, and human rights groups under the name "Project Galileo".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2017, it extended the service to electoral infrastructure and political campaigns under the name "Athenian Project".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] By 2025, more than 2,900 users and organizations were participating in Project Galileo, including 31 US states.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In February 2014, Cloudflare claimed to have mitigated an NTP reflection attack against an unnamed European customer, which it stated peaked at 400 Gbit/s.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In November 2014, it reported a 500 Gbit/s DDoS attack in Hong Kong.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In July 2021, the company claimed to have absorbed a DDoS attack three times larger than any it had previously recorded, which its corporate blog implied was over 1.2 Tbit/s in total.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In February 2023, Cloudflare reported blocking a 71 million request-per-second DDoS attack which "the company says was the largest HTTP DDoS attack on record".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare blocked the then largest publicly recorded DDoS attack in August 2025, with volumetric attacks peaking at 11.5 terabits per second (tbps).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] This was surpassed in December 2025 when an Aisuru botnet launched a 31.4 tbps attack, with a requests-per-second rate exceeding 200 million, against multiple companies in the telecommunications sector, a campaign Cloudflare dubbed "The Night Before Christmas".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In April 2026, Cloudflare released a system designed to let users implement their own custom DDoS mitigation logic, using protocols built on User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2017, Cloudflare launched Cloudflare Workers, a serverless computing platform for creating new applications, augmenting existing ones, without configuring or maintaining infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] It has expanded to include Workers KV, a low-latency key-value data store; Cron Triggers, for scheduling Cron jobs; and additional tooling for developers to deploy and scale their code across the globe.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2020, Cloudflare released a JAMstack platform for developers to deploy websites on Cloudflare's Edge infrastructure, under the name "Pages".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2022, Cloudflare announced an Edge SQL database, D1, which is built on SQLite.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare and IBM announced a partnership providing bot management capabilities to protect IBM Cloud customers from malicious bots and automated threats.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The same month, Cloudflare was hired by SpaceX to boost the performance of Starlink.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In September, the company launched Cloudflare Fonts as a competitor to Google Fonts.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In April 2020, Cloudflare announced it was moving away from using reCAPTCHA in favor of hCaptcha.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In September 2022, Cloudflare began to test Turnstile – an alternative to CAPTCHA.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The product, instead of presenting a visual CAPTCHA for the user to solve, automatizes the verification process by conducting JavaScript-based checks inside the browser to determine whether the user is a real person or an automated entity.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The algorithm reportedly uses machine learning to optimize the process.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Through a contract with the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, Cloudflare provides registry and authoritative DNS services to the .gov top-level domain.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare also launched Cloudflare for Campaigns in 2020, to offer free cybersecurity tools to political campaigns.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Those tools expanded to include secure email systems in 2025.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In November 2020, Cloudflare announced Cloudflare for Teams, consisting of a DNS resolver and web gateway called "Gateway", and a zero-trust authentication service called "Access".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare released an Oblivious HTTP relay service in 2022, called Privacy Gateway.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced a partnership with PhonePe in January 2023 to secure its mobile payment system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In February, Cloudflare launched Wildebeest to allow Mastodon users to set up and run their own instances on Cloudflare's infrastructure.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In August 2023, Cloudflare started the Project Cybersafe Schools program as part of a $20 million grant program from Amazon Web Services, making 70 percent of public school districts in the United States eligible for no-cost cybersecurity services.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In March 2024, it announced Firewall for AI to defend applications running large language models (LLMs).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In September, Cloudflare announced Ephemeral IDs, which identifies fraudulent activity by linking behavior to a client through a short-lived, generated ID, rather than the traditional means of using an IP address.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The same month, the company also announced all ISP and equipment manufacturers could use its DNS resolvers for free.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare introduced the Cloudforce One threat events platform in March 2025, offering real-time insights into cyberattacks using data gathered from Cloudflare's network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare's overarching secure access service edge (SASE) platform debuted in October 2020.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare announced the acquisition of Area 1 Security in February 2022, a company who developed a product designed to combat phishing email attacks.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare acquired Nefeli Networks in March 2024, a cloud networking company, co-founded by computer scientist Sylvia Ratnasamy.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare released a VPN-like service called WARP, and open sourced the custom underlying WireGuard implementation written in Rust.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In January 2021, the company began providing its "Waiting Room" digital queue product for free for COVID-19 vaccination scheduling under the title "Project Fair Shot".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Project Fair Shot later won a Webby People's Choice Award in 2022 for Event Management under the Apps & Software category.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In March 2023, Cloudflare announced post-quantum cryptography will be made freely and forever available to cloud services, applications and Internet connections.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare released the Speed Brain and Instant Purge features in September 2024, to significantly reduce page load latency by prefetching content, and invalidating cached content in under 150ms.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2024, Cloudflare announced plans to launch a new payment method, called Stripe Link, which went into beta in the fall.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Since 2010, Cloudflare has collaborated with the National Center for Missing & Exploited Children to provide data, files, and supplemental investigation from abuse reports observed on its network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare designed a new NCMEC reporting system in 2024, updating it in 2025 by integrating Cloudflare Workflows and making the CSAM scanning tool accessible globally.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On June 1, 2012, the hacker group UGNazi compromised some of Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince's accounts and redirected visitors of the website 4chan to a Twitter account belonging to UGNazi.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] They allegedly used social engineering to trick AT&T support staff into giving them access to Prince's voicemail, then exploited a vulnerability in Cloudflare's use of Google's two-factor authentication system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Once in control of Prince's email account, UGNazi was able to redirect the 4chan domain through Cloudflare's database.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] From September 2016 until February 2017, a Cloudflare bug nicknamed Cloudbleed leaked sensitive data, including passwords and authentication tokens, from customer websites by sending extra data in response to web requests.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On November 18, 2025, Cloudflare suffered a major global outage that caused widespread 500 errors, slowing down many platforms, making them unreachable or completely down for users around the world.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Access to WARP, Cloudflare's VPN service, was also briefly disabled in London.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] During the outage, a spokesperson for Cloudflare said the company had seen a "spike in unusual traffic", causing some traffic passing through its network to experience errors.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] At 14:23 UTC, *The Guardian* reported that Cloudflare had released a fix.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] It also reported that maintenance was due at various locations, though this is not known to have caused the outages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] At 14:42 UTC, Cloudflare informed users on its status page that the fix had been implemented and that it would take some time for remaining post-deployment issues to be fixed.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] A technical postmortem of the incident was released the day following the outage.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare attributed the outage to a change in the configuration of a database, which caused an invalid file to be sent to all servers on the network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On December 5, Cloudflare suffered another global outage, which began at 09:00 AM UTC.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] This was the second such outage in three weeks to affect Cloudflare's services.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In January 2026, security researchers disclosed a vulnerability in Cloudflare's Web application firewall (WAF) that allowed attackers to bypass security rules and access origin servers directly.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The flaw existed in the handling of ACME challenge requests; the logic disabled WAF protections for requests targeting the `/.well-known/acme-challenge/` path without sufficiently verifying if the token matched an active validation attempt.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare patched the vulnerability in October 2025, stating that the issue was a logic flaw rather than a code execution vulnerability and that there was no evidence of exploitation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has established a content neutrality policy and opposes the policing of its customers on the basis of free speech unless said customers break the law.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company has faced criticism for not banning hate speech websites and websites allegedly connected to terrorism groups.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has maintained that no law enforcement agency has asked the company to discontinue these services and it closely monitors its obligations under U.S. laws.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2022, a research paper by Stanford University found that Cloudflare was a prominent CDN provider, among several other providers, that are disproportionately responsible for serving misinformation websites.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has come under pressure due to its services being utilized to access far-right content.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DNS routing and DDoS protection for the white supremacist and neo-Nazi website *The Daily Stormer*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2017, after previously refusing to take any action against the website, Cloudflare stopped providing its services to *The Daily Stormer* after an announcement on the website asserted that Cloudflare executives were privately supporting its ideology.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] As a self-described "free speech absolutist", Prince claimed he did not want to repeat the decision, and sought out protections for the company should they be faced with a similar situation in the future.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Prince further addressed the dangers of large companies deciding what is allowed to stay online, a concern shared by a number of civil liberties groups and privacy experts.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The Electronic Frontier Foundation, a US digital rights group, said that services such as Cloudflare should not be deciding what speech is acceptable and that illegal content should be handled through the legal system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2019, Cloudflare was criticized for providing services to the far-right discussion and imageboard 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The message board has been linked to mass shootings in the United States and the Christchurch mosque shootings in New Zealand.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In addition, a number of news organizations including *The Washington Post* and *The Daily Dot* have reported on the existence of child pornography and child sexual abuse discussion boards.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] A Cloudflare representative said that the platform "does not host the referenced websites, cannot block websites, and is not in the business of hiding companies that host illegal content".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare did not terminate service to 8chan until public and legal pressure mounted in the wake of the 2019 El Paso shooting, in which the associated manifesto was published to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In an interview with *The Guardian* immediately after the shooting, CEO Matthew Prince defended Cloudflare's support of 8chan, saying that he had a "moral obligation" to keep 8chan online.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On August 5, 2019, two days after Prince's interview with The Guardian, Cloudflare terminated service to 8chan.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare explained that 8chan "have proven themselves to be lawless and that lawlessness has caused multiple tragic deaths.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare provided DDoS mitigation and acted as a reverse proxy for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The site often engages in harassment and doxxing of targets and has been implicated in the suicides of at least three people.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Kiwi Farms also has a reputation for transphobic content, and its users have been accused of swatting vulnerable individuals.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Although Cloudflare was not the primary website host, it did perform critical services to keep Kiwi Farms on-line, both protecting the site from denial-of-service attacks and optimizing content delivery.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2022, a campaign was launched by transgender activist Clara Sorrenti, who has previously been targeted by the forum, to pressure Cloudflare into terminating service for Kiwi Farms.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare responded by issuing a statement on its abuse policies and saying it didn't want to set precedent for speech on the internet with its "extraordinary" decision.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company also released a blog post and likened its services to that of a public utility, emphasizing that it does not believe in shutting down security services based on content it finds objectionable.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] They acknowledged that while it might be more popular to remove sites that the Cloudflare team finds offensive, it stood by its decision not to do so.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The company also defended its decision by saying that it donated all earnings from anti-LGBTIQ+ sites to an organization that advocated for LGBTIQ+ rights.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On September 3, 2022, Cloudflare blocked Kiwi Farms, citing urgent escalating rhetoric against targets of Kiwi Farms, stating that there is an "unprecedented emergency and immediate threat to human life".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Switter was a social media network for the sex worker community, built by Australia-based company Assembly Four on Mastodon's open-source software, before Cloudflare dropped Switter as a client and ceased services in April 2018, citing terms of service violations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] This occurred shortly after the passage of FOSTA/SESTA, a set of bills criminalizing websites that facilitate or support sex trafficking in 2018.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] SESTA weakened protections for Internet infrastructure companies and was criticized on free speech grounds due to concerns about disproportionate impact and disruptions to the lives of sex workers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare said the move was "related to our attempts to understand FOSTA, which is a very bad law and [sets] a very dangerous precedent".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Assembly Four said that "Given Cloudflare's previous stances of privacy and freedom, as well as fighting alongside the EFF, we had hoped they would take a stand against FOSTA/SESTA".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2015, testimony to the United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs, it was reported that two of the top three online chat forums and nearly forty other web sites belonging to the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL) were guarded by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been cited in reports by The Spamhaus Project, an international spam tracking organization, for the high numbers of cybercriminal botnet operations hosted by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] An October 2015 report found that Cloudflare provisioned 40% of the SSL certificates used by typosquatting phishing sites, which use deceptive domain names resembling those of banks and payment processors to compromise Internet users' banking and other transactions.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare has been criticized for having a conflict of interest by providing DDoS protection to both the operators and victims of "stresser" services.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2018, Cloudflare was identified by the European Union's Counterfeit and Piracy Watch List as a "notorious market" which engages in, facilitates, or benefits from counterfeiting and piracy.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The report noted that Cloudflare hides and anonymizes the operators of 40% of the world's pirate sites, and 62% of the 500 largest such sites, and "does not follow due diligence when opening accounts for websites to prevent illegal sites from using its services".
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2020, an Italian court ruled Cloudflare had to block current and future domain names and IP addresses of the pirate IPTV service "IPTV THE BEST" for infringing on Lega Serie A intellectual property.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] At the time, Cloudflare was already blocking 22 domain names in Italy.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Following the December 2024 court ruling, the Spanish LaLiga requested that telephone operators block Cloudflare's IP address ranges in February 2025.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare hosted websites that illegally broadcast soccer matches.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] As a result, the pirate platform DuckVision was shut down before the derby between Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The platform had 200,000 users and was backed by Cloudflare.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] The blocks affected major legitimate websites, including X, Vimeo, Steam, GitHub, and the Royal Spanish Academy.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare CEO Matthew Prince responded that the company decided to remain providing services to Russian people to counter Russia's attempts to raise a 'digital iron curtain'.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] Cloudflare's Project Galileo, launched in 2014, offers DDoS protection to NGOs for free.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2022, they extended free protection to Ukrainian government and telecoms.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] In 2022, Japanese publishers Shueisha, Kodansha, Shogakukan, and Kadokawa Shoten filed a copyright lawsuit against Cloudflare, alleging that the service was distributing data to manga piracy sites and sought an injunction and ¥460 million (US$4 million) in damages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] On November 19, 2025, a judge ruled in favor of the publishers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/cloudflare] While the ruling recognized approximately ¥3.6 billion (US$24 million) in damages, Cloudflare was ordered to pay a total amount of ¥500 million (US$3.6 million), as the publishers claimed that Cloudflare was only partially responsible for the damages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
[src:cloudflare-durable-objects/strong-consistency] Therefore, only one consistent state can be observed, as opposed to weak consistency, where different parallel processes (or nodes, etc.) can perceive variables in different states.
